expPurpose: What do you think the experiment was about?
Q1: I can easily tell if someone else wants to enter a conversation.
Q2: I find it difficult to explain to others things that I understand easily, when they don't understand it the first time.
Q3: I really enjoy caring for other people.
Q4: I find it hard to know what to do in a social situation.
Q5: People often tell me that I went too far in driving my point home in a discussion.
Q6: It doesn't bother me too much if I am late meeting a friend.
Q7: Friendships and relationships are just too difficult, so I tend not to bother with them.
Q8: I often find it difficult to judge if something is rude or polite.
Q9: In a conversation, I tend to focus on my own thoughts rather than on what my listener might be thinking.
Q10: When I was a child, I enjoyed cutting up worms to see what would happen.
Q11: I can pick up quickly if someone says one thing but means another.
Q12: It is hard for me to see why some things upset people so much.
Q13: I find it easy to put myself in somebody else's shoes.
Q14: I am good at predicting how someone will feel.
Q15: I am quick to spot when someone in a group is feeling awkward or uncomfortable.
Q16: If I say something that someone else is offended by, I think that that's their problem, not mine.
Q17: If anyone asked me if I like their haricut, I would reply truthfully, even if I didn't like it.
Q18: I can't always see why someone should have felt offended by a remark.
Q19: Seeing people cry doesn't really upset me.
Q20: I am very blunt, which some people take to be rudeness, even though this is unintentional.
Q21: I don't tend to find social situations confusing
Q22: Other people tell me I am good at understanding how they are feeling and what they are thinking.
Q23: When I talk to people, I tend to talk about their experiences rather than my own.
Q24: It upsets me to see animals in pain.
Q25: I am able to make decisions without being influenced by people's feelings.
Q26: I can easily tell if someone else is interested or bored with what I am saying.
Q27: I get upset if I see people suffering on news programmes.
Q28: Friends usually talk to me about their problems as they say I am very understanding.
Q29: I can sense if I am intruding, even if the other person doesn't tell me.
Q30: People sometimes tell me that I have gone too far with teasing.
Q31: Other people often say that I am insensitive, though I don't always see why.
Q32: If I see a stranger in a group, I think that it is up to them to make an effort to join in.
Q33: I usually stay emotionally detached when watching a film.
Q34: I can tune into how someone else feels rapidly and intuitively.
Q35: I can easily work out what another person might want to talk about.
Q36: I can tell if someone is masking their true emotion.
Q37: I don't consciously work out the rules of social situations.
Q38: I am good at predicting what someone will do.
Q39: I tend to get emotionally involved with a friend's problems.
Q40: I can usually appreciate the other person's viewpoint, even if I don't agree with it.

expPurpose: I think the experiment was seeing how well we perceive differences in voice from those who sound like us and those with accents.
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Canadians tend to use more British style pronunciations and words such as color vs. colour.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: I think Canadians put more emphasis on "our" sounds.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: More emphasis on the ou sounds compared to American English.

expPurpose: Biases in distinguishing accents
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Canadians and Michiganders use different vowel sounds for the same words (e.g. "ou" in "about" is pronounced differently).
EK2.CanPron.Diff: Same as previous response - they use different vowel sounds for the same words.
EK3.CanAI.Diff_1_TEXT: Canadians pronounce the "i" sound higher and slightly longer in these words than Michiganders do.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: Michiganders pronounce "ou" the same as "ow" whereas Canadians have a separate vowel sound for "ou" that is somewhere in between "ow" and "oo."

expPurpose: Identifying if there are similarities between tones and pronunciation
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: The ou sound is more pronounced in Canadian English
EK2.CanPron.Diff: The ou is drawn out for Canadians. The Michigan ones are quicker and sound like ow
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: Moure pronounced in Canadian english and drawn out

expPurpose: Understanding differences better after hearing them more
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Different inflections on syllables
EK2.CanPron.Diff:
Michigan - About
Canada - Aboot
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT:
Michigan - more emphasis on the out (owt)
Canada - Less emphasis (oot)

expPurpose: good
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: good
EK2.CanPron.Diff: good

expPurpose: To determine which pronunciation of the word is similar to each other
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Sometimes there's a difference in which syllable gets the emphasis put on it
EK2.CanPron.Diff: I notice that sometimes Canadians will put the emphasis on the first part of a word and that some words will have different meanings
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: The "ou" vowels have the emphasis put on them more strongly than Michiganders will put. Canadians use the long 'u' sound and Michiganders will use the short "u"

expPurpose: Supposedly it was on language perception - how similar sounding words were when spoken with different inflections by the same person,
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Canadians say eh more than people from Michigan (except in the upper peninsula.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: Sorry, I answered the last question with pronunciation differences. Canadians use "eh" more often than MIchiganders in the lower peninsula.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: A Canadian pronounces "About" more like aboot.

expPurpose: I would say pronounciation, but I actually think it was an endurance test.  To see if people could stay focused.
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Northern Michigan speaks closer to Canadian English.  Big difference is the vowel pronounciation.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: Vowels.  Specifically o's.

expPurpose: To see if people will make up a difference between the sounds after hearing them long enough.
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: I feel that Canadian and Michigan English are the closest in sounding alike, while other states sound a lot more different.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: I can not name any off the top of my head, but there are a few, Michigan English is mostly like Canadian English though.

expPurpose: how we hear different sounds in michigan and canada
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: the sound is different

expPurpose: I think the experiment was to see how people from different parts of America understand different pronunciations of words, and to see how different parts of the words are said in different areas.
SpHDisorder_2_TEXT: I have had a stuttering issue since I was around 5-6.
LingExp: 2 Years of Spanish in High School
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Being from Michigan and listening to the audio, I noticed that people from Michigan under pronounced some letters, whereas from Canada, they sounded our letters like O an I more. Also with Canadian English, it sounded slightly more European while still having a mainly American accent.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: Canadian English sounds like it pronounces letters a bit more than Michigan English would such as O and I. I feel like the word "Without" for example would be pronounced slightly different in Canada than it is in Michigan.
EK3.CanAI.Diff_1_TEXT: I think that the "I" in those words would be more pronounced than it would be in Michigan English.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: I feel like in Michigan we don't usually pronounce the "O" as much as the would in Canadian English.

expPurpose: differences in accents between Michigan and Canada
SK1.WhereStandard: Northern East Coast, West coast, Most of the Northern Midwest
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: I don't have any specific examples in mind, but there are a couple YouTube channels I watch with Canadian hosts and I'll hear an accent here and there.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: I don't have any specific examples in mind, but I've heard an accent from Canadian speakers on YouTube (and other places) as I mentioned before. If I was on the street and heard someone from Canada talking without knowing them, I'm not sure I would be able to identify the accent as Canadian though.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: With the word 'about', I heard it more as "a-boot" sometimes. With "out" I think I've heard more emphasis on the 'O' more like and "owe-ut". With 'house' I've as a more like who-use, sort of.

expPurpose: subtle differences in sound, can affect hearing and change word or enunciation... was the word sight or cite for example
SpHDisorder_2_TEXT: slight cauliflower ear in the left ear,  so ear buds dont fit exactly and fall out and even with headphones there is a slight muffle to the left side where damaged, right side is fine. I seem to have an 80/100 hearing according to last doctors visit
SK1.WhereStandard: Not michigan - half our state has an accent
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: longer enunciation on some words, sharper delivery on some. There are subtle and then major differences depending on region and how thick an accent are. My west coast canadian friends sound entirely different than east coast canadian friends and they both say I have an accent from michigan
EK2.CanPron.Diff: its hard to say, but just watch fargo with their accent and drawl on words, is how i picture our northern neighbors to us --  and its even more pronounced the french canadians who speak english, its just an accent that affects delivery a little bit
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: how we say "about", they almost are portrayed as french Canadians and seem to have picked up and say "aboot" (as do people in Wisconsin or Minnesota)

expPurpose: I am not sure.  Differences in pronunciation between American and Canadian accents?  Some of the words spoken had a definite difference, where some sounded completely the same.
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: The main one that I can think of is how some words with -ou in them are pronounced.  Like "about" for example.  I would say a-BOWT, with the "O" sounding like "ow" like when someone hurts themselves.  I think some Canadian people say a-BOOT.  That might be a little bit of an exaggeration, but there is a definite difference.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: The main one I can think of is as i said before - the pronunciation of words with -ou in them.  In MIchigan we pronounce them "ow" with a short "o".  In Canada I have heard them pronounced more like "oo".  With some people the, difference is slight, but with others, it is much more prounounced.
EK3.CanAI.Diff_1_TEXT: Not sure, but I think the "i" might sound more like the word "aye" rather than like a long "i".
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: In Michigan we would pronounce -ou like "ow" as in "Ow, that hurt."  With Canadian English, It sounds more similar to "-oo".  Every one is different.  In some, the difference is very slight, but in other cases it is definitely different.

expPurpose: Your accuracy when hearing someone of your region speak when compared to hearing someone of another region speak
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Michiganders tend to speak very nasally compared to other English speakers, and Canadians tend to emphasize their o sounds. Comparing Gretchen Whitmer and Justin Trudeau, there is a slight, but distinctive, difference between them.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: As mentioned before, our vowels are slightly different from each other

expPurpose: Evaluating subtle differences in word sounds between two places with seeming identical sounding accents and whether native residents can determine these differences.
LingExp: I've taken one speech class in high school.
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Mainly subtle differences in pronouncing certain vowel sounds, a slight French influence.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: Stereotypically, "about" sounds like "aboot".  Most "ow" sounds tend to sound like "oo" when spoken by Canadians, to my ear at least.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: As I mentioned, "ow" sounds trail into "oo" sounds.

EK1.CanSpeak.Diff:
Canadians don't say "out" with an "ow" sound like how. They say it like "oat" or "oot", like "about" becomes "aboat" or "aboot."

Also they finish their sentences with "eh" a lot.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: The words about and out are said differently by Canadians.  They would say "aboot" or "oot".
